### ── Adaptive Engine API Tests ──────────────────────────────────────────
### Run any request by clicking "Send Request" above it

### 1. Health Check
GET http://localhost:8000/health

###

### 2. Start Session
POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/session/start
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "user_id": "student_001",
    "starting_difficulty": 1
}

###

### 3. Get Next Question  (paste your session_token below)
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/question/next/PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE

###

### 4. Submit Answer
POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/answer/submit
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "session_token": "PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE",
    "question_id": 1,
    "answer_text": "A variable is a named storage location in memory that holds a value which can change during program execution.",
    "time_taken_seconds": 35.0,
    "paste_detected": false
}

###

### 5. Submit Suspicious Answer (triggers anti-cheat flags)
POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/answer/submit
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "session_token": "PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE",
    "question_id": 2,
    "answer_text": "A list is mutable (changeable) and uses square brackets. A tuple is immutable (unchangeable) and uses parentheses. Lists support append, remove, sort. Tuples are faster and memory-efficient for fixed data.",
    "time_taken_seconds": 0.8,
    "paste_detected": true
}

###

### 6. Security Report
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/security/report/PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE

###

### 7. Difficulty Status
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/difficulty/status/PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE

###

### 8. Answer History
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/answer/history/PASTE_SESSION_TOKEN_HERE

###

### 9. List All Questions
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/questions/list

###

### 10. List Easy Questions Only
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/questions/list?difficulty=1

###

### 11. Add New Question
POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/question/add
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "question_text": "What is the difference between a stack and a queue?",
    "expected_answer": "A stack uses LIFO (Last In First Out) - the last item added is the first removed, like a stack of plates. A queue uses FIFO (First In First Out) - the first item added is first removed, like a queue of people.",
    "difficulty_level": 2,
    "topic": "data_structures"
}

###

### 12. Cache / Redis Status
GET http://localhost:8000/api/v1/cache/status
